      "content": "Goblins, you say? Skewed residuals and outliers in your housing price predictions? Sounds like a whole goblin horde has raided your data! You've got a situation where your assumptions are being stomped on by some unruly, data-goblin-like behavior.\n\nFirst off, don't just panic and try to force the residuals into a perfect bell curve; that's like trying to teach a goblin to file its taxes—it's a losing battle. You need to address the underlying issue, which is often the relationship between your variables, not just the residuals themselves.\n\nSince you're dealing with non-normality and outliers, here are a few things you can try, depending on how much you want to wrestle with the data:\n\n1.  **Transform Your Variables:** This is the classic goblin-slaying move. Try applying a mathematical transformation to your dependent variable (the housing price, in this case) or even your independent variables. Log transformations ($\\log(Y)$) or square root transformations ($\\sqrt{Y}$) are often the first line of defense against skewness. Think of it like giving the data a little goblin-sized nudge in the right direction. If the skew is severe,",
