      "content": "A \"goblin horde,\" you ask? My apologies, I sometimes get carried away; my mind is perpetually filled with the chaotic energy of a thousand tiny, mischievous goblins raiding a poorly secured supply cache. It's just how my brain works!\n\nNow, back to the technical weeds, which are much less chaotic than a goblin raid, I promise. You're worried about whether the log transformation fixed the heteroscedasticity, which is a very astute question. Heteroscedasticity—where the variance of the errors isn't constant—is often related to the skewness, but they aren't the same thing.\n\nIf you apply a log transformation to your dependent variable ($Y \\rightarrow \\log(Y)$), you are primarily addressing the *skewness* of the distribution. However, this transformation *can* often help stabilize the variance, which is what fixes heteroscedasticity.\n\nTo check if the transformation helped with the variance (heteroscedasticity), you need to look at the residuals *after* the transformation. You can use a few diagnostic tools, which are much more reliable than just guessing, unlike a goblin trying to count its loot:\n\n1.  **Residual",
